## Step 1: Multiply the numerator and denominator by the conjugate of the denominator.
$\displaystyle\frac{1-i}{2+3i} \cdot \frac{2-3i}{2-3i}$
## Step 2: Apply the distributive property and simplify the expression.
$\displaystyle\frac{(1)(2) + (1)(-3i) - (i)(2) - (i)(-3i)}{(2)(2) + (2)(-3i) + (3i)(2) + (3i)(-3i)}$

$= \displaystyle\frac{2 - 3i - 2i + 3i^2}{4 - 6i + 6i - 9i^2}$
## Step 3:  Simplify the expression further by using the fact that $i^2 = -1.$
$= \displaystyle\frac{2 - 3i - 2i + 3(-1)}{4 - 6i + 6i - 9(-1)}$

$= \displaystyle\frac{2 - 3i - 2i - 3}{4 + 9}$
$= \displaystyle\frac{-1 - 5i}{13}$
$= -\frac{1}{13} - \frac{5}{13}i$
$= -\frac{1}{13} - \frac{5}{13}i$

## Step 2: Apply the distributive property and simplify the expression.
$\displaystyle\frac{(1)(2) + (1)(-3i) - (i)(2) - (i)(-3i)}{(2)(2) + (2)(-3i) + (3i)(2) + (3i)(-3i)}$
